    {
      "id": "lkuAbC6OWrjnp0x-q8Y23",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 925.1352269025706,
      "y": 1298.9076887304382,
      "width": 1013.0560302734375,
      "height": 1100,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 0,
      "opacity": 80,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b6m",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1863574778,
      "version": 12639,
      "versionNonce": 916490702,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1774362801651,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "* Les différents types de claim, et leurs indices de vérifiabilité associés : \n\nA - Common Knowledge:\n\n> factual_common_knowledge: will be answered directly. \n  For example, \"Does the sun rotate around the earth\" doesn't need justification today.  \n\nB - Verifiable Claims: \n\nThose claims will only go through the fact-checking pipeline, we know for sure we're not gonna need more.  \n> factual: a claim about a precise fact, that we can check true/false with data. \n> statistical: similar to factual, but the workflow will need to be more vigilant to the context, \n  the sample, the year of study.\n> quote: to know if someone said something, we must focus more on speech archives, interviews etc. \n  (pas possible de checker tout un compte insta par exemple...). Le contexte est souvent TRES important. \n> event: events are often mischaracterized (ex: \"voted\" vs \"discussed\" vs \"proposed\"). Must be careful about this. \n\nC - Partly-Verifiable Claims: \n\nThose claims will go through the fact-checking pipeline first, but because they are less verifiable or hold other claims \nimplicitly, the generated queries will need to be smarter. Some data exist, some studies have been conducted, but \nthey can contradict, and they may not be enough to settle the debate. It must then push the analysis to the \nlevel-3 if sources dont converge (or not if the user is in Economy Mode). If they converge, level-2 is sufficient. \nA level-2 conclusion would be \"It cannot be decided easily, studies diverge. It depends on criterias A, B, C...\". \nThe level-3 answer would explain for example: \"The left-wing party leans more towards this, puts more emphasis \non this side of the issue, whereas the right-wing...\"\n> causal: Studies exist on the topic, but causality can rarely be proven at 100%. The workflow should assess if \n  there is a consensus or not, if it's only a correlation... Example: \"Social networks cause depression among teenagers\". \n> comparative: The workflow must often frame the topic better. Example: \"Coffee is more dangerous than alcohol\" --> What\n  does \"dangerous\" mean here? Depending on the interpretation, are there studies proving it? \n> predictive: An affirmation about the future. It can naturally not be verifiable, but its credibility can be assessed. What\n  are the underlying assumptions, who does it, hare there studies about it? Example: \"AI will replace 50% of jobs within 5 years\". \n\nD - Non-Verifiable Claims:\n\nNo fact-checking is possible. A critical analysis can be conducted on the subject. \n> opinion: a value judgment or a political opinion based on beliefs, sentiments, personal values, instead of objective facts. \n  For exemple: \"Phones should be banned for people under 16\" --> It needs to be contextualized, adversary points of\n  view must be explained, backed up by the relevant data/studies. \n\nE - Invalid Topics: \n\nThe topics that are outside of the editorial perimeter of my platform:\n- religious matters\n- philosophical questions\n- all kinds of personal advice (financial, judicial, medical, course of action, personal development...)\n- commercial content \n- everything illegal (\"nazis were not bad\" --> Negationism is illegal)\n- questions about entertainment, sport, art, pop-culture (\"is this movie good?\" / \"is Mbappe better than Haaland\")\n- pure technical and scientific questions\n- psychological and relational advice (\"how to deal with my toxic boss?\")\n- content creation (\"write an article/email/video for me\")\n- astrology, paranormal, pseudo-sciences\nThis list is not exhaustive. In the prompt, I will also specify to the agent what IS the accepted perimeter: \n--> Verifiable or debatable affirmations, political debates, news debates, society debates. ",
      "fontSize": 16,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "* Les différents types de claim, et leurs indices de vérifiabilité associés : \n\nA - Common Knowledge:\n\n> factual_common_knowledge: will be answered directly. \n  For example, \"Does the sun rotate around the earth\" doesn't need justification today.  \n\nB - Verifiable Claims: \n\nThose claims will only go through the fact-checking pipeline, we know for sure we're not gonna need more.  \n> factual: a claim about a precise fact, that we can check true/false with data. \n> statistical: similar to factual, but the workflow will need to be more vigilant to the context, \n  the sample, the year of study.\n> quote: to know if someone said something, we must focus more on speech archives, interviews etc. \n  (pas possible de checker tout un compte insta par exemple...). Le contexte est souvent TRES important. \n> event: events are often mischaracterized (ex: \"voted\" vs \"discussed\" vs \"proposed\"). Must be careful about this. \n\nC - Partly-Verifiable Claims: \n\nThose claims will go through the fact-checking pipeline first, but because they are less verifiable or hold other claims \nimplicitly, the generated queries will need to be smarter. Some data exist, some studies have been conducted, but \nthey can contradict, and they may not be enough to settle the debate. It must then push the analysis to the \nlevel-3 if sources dont converge (or not if the user is in Economy Mode). If they converge, level-2 is sufficient. \nA level-2 conclusion would be \"It cannot be decided easily, studies diverge. It depends on criterias A, B, C...\". \nThe level-3 answer would explain for example: \"The left-wing party leans more towards this, puts more emphasis \non this side of the issue, whereas the right-wing...\"\n> causal: Studies exist on the topic, but causality can rarely be proven at 100%. The workflow should assess if \n  there is a consensus or not, if it's only a correlation... Example: \"Social networks cause depression among teenagers\". \n> comparative: The workflow must often frame the topic better. Example: \"Coffee is more dangerous than alcohol\" --> What\n  does \"dangerous\" mean here? Depending on the interpretation, are there studies proving it? \n> predictive: An affirmation about the future. It can naturally not be verifiable, but its credibility can be assessed. What\n  are the underlying assumptions, who does it, hare there studies about it? Example: \"AI will replace 50% of jobs within 5 years\". \n\nD - Non-Verifiable Claims:\n\nNo fact-checking is possible. A critical analysis can be conducted on the subject. \n> opinion: a value judgment or a political opinion based on beliefs, sentiments, personal values, instead of objective facts. \n  For exemple: \"Phones should be banned for people under 16\" --> It needs to be contextualized, adversary points of\n  view must be explained, backed up by the relevant data/studies. \n\nE - Invalid Topics: \n\nThe topics that are outside of the editorial perimeter of my platform:\n- religious matters\n- philosophical questions\n- all kinds of personal advice (financial, judicial, medical, course of action, personal development...)\n- commercial content \n- everything illegal (\"nazis were not bad\" --> Negationism is illegal)\n- questions about entertainment, sport, art, pop-culture (\"is this movie good?\" / \"is Mbappe better than Haaland\")\n- pure technical and scientific questions\n- psychological and relational advice (\"how to deal with my toxic boss?\")\n- content creation (\"write an article/email/video for me\")\n- astrology, paranormal, pseudo-sciences\nThis list is not exhaustive. In the prompt, I will also specify to the agent what IS the accepted perimeter: \n--> Verifiable or debatable affirmations, political debates, news debates, society debates. ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
